Procedia Computer Science 9 (2012) 1930 ‚Äì 1939

Reducing Library Overheads through Source-to-Source Translation
Alden King, Scott Baden
University of California, San Diego

Abstract
Object oriented application libraries targeted to a speciÔ¨Åc application domain are an attractive means of reducing
the software development time for sophisticated high performance applications. However, libraries can have the
drawback of high abstraction penalties. We describe a domain speciÔ¨Åc, source-to-source translator that eliminates
abstraction penalties in an array class library used to analyze turbulent Ô¨Çow simulation data. Our translator eÔ¨Äectively
Ô¨Çattens the abstractions, yielding performance within 75% of C code that uses primitive C arrays and no user-deÔ¨Åned
abstractions.

1. Introduction
Over the past few decades, advances in computational infrastructure and numerical methods have delivered simulations of unprecedented Ô¨Ådelity and accuracy, leading to new scientiÔ¨Åc discovery. However, a side eÔ¨Äect of this
‚Äúcomputational revolution‚Äù is the prodigious output of simulation data that challenges our ability to infer the relevant
science. For example, there are important applications where the dynamics may be dominated by coherent structures
and patterns, but these may be diÔ¨Écult to deÔ¨Åne, let alone understand. While visualization is an important tool for
understanding pattern evolution, the process is subjective, not scalable to the study of populations of structures and
patterns, and does not directly quantify the contribution of coherent structures to Ô¨Çow properties.
By and large, the CFD community relies on ad-hoc analysis tools that are customized to a speciÔ¨Åc application and
must be painstakingly recoded for each new usage pattern. While there do exist some publicly available tools [1], they
present the user with predeÔ¨Åned or ‚Äúcanned‚Äù primitives. When a new need arises, there may be no way to optimize
user-authored extensions since the existing framework is designed to optimize only built-in functionality.
We previously developed Saaz, a C++ library for authoring extensible analysis tools for study of turbulent Ô¨Çow
simulations [2]. We attached Saaz to running simulations and were eÔ¨Äectively able to increase the time resolution of
Ô¨Çow analysis by Ô¨Åltering data based on user-speciÔ¨Åed criteria, reducing the rate at which simulated data was committed
to disk. Saaz‚Äôs performance was not an issue because the domain scientists did not need to analyze every time step of
the simulation: the cost of Saaz‚Äôs authored analyses was just 10% of the execution time of the simulator.
When we look at oÔ¨Ñine datasets, however, the picture changes. With oÔ¨Ñine analysis, there is no simulator to overwhelm the cost of analysis in Saaz. We determined that Saaz incurs overheads from its use of class abstractions that
